<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="citations">
    <title>Citations</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>We'll just go ahead and say it: citations are a pain. While everyone agrees that clear references to the sources you use are essential to good scholarship, almost no one likes actually keeping track of and writing out citations. But, alas, they must be done! We hope that this section will enable you to think about citations in a new way, one less about memorizing styles and more about understanding the conceptual and practical foundations of citing sources.</p>
    </introduction>
    <section xml:id="the-basics">
        <title>The Basics</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>When writing citations, the most basic question you need to ask yourself is: <q>What information would someone need to find this source on their own?</q> Although nowadays you'd likely use your phone to take a picture of a product you want to be able to find again (your favorite brand of bread, for example), citations require a little more effort. The basic principle, however, is the same. When taking a picture to remember something, you make sure that you have the name and any other identifying information that will help you find it again. Similarly, when writing a citation, you want to make sure you include the basic identifying features of a source, namely the author, title, date, and publisher.</p>
            <p>Citations serve many purposes. Beyond allowing others to <em>find</em> the sources you use, citations also give your audience clues about the type of information you've used, where that information came from, and how reliable the information is within a particular context, all without having to go find the source directly. There are two main categories of each citation style: in-text citations and full citations. In-text citations provide a reader with immediate information about the source from which a piece of information came. Full citations provide a reader with more complete information about the source.</p>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>Background</title>
            <p>In this chapter, we'll discuss the three major citation styles you'll encounter during your time at Puget Sound: MLA, Chicago (CMS), and APA.</p>
            <p>In general, here are some differences between the styles:</p>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/citation-styles-table"/>
            </sidebyside>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Basic Components</title>
            <p>No matter the style, the basic components you need for each type of source remain relatively constant. Here are the components for a few types of frequently-used sources:</p>
            <sidebyside>
                <list>
                    <title>Books</title>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Author(s)</p></li>
                        <li><p>Title</p></li>
                        <li><p>Date</p></li>
                        <li><p>Publisher</p></li>
                        <li><p>Publisher location</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <title>Journal Articles</title>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Author(s)</p></li>
                        <li><p>Title</p></li>
                        <li><p>Date</p></li>
                        <li><p>Publisher (AKA the journal name)</p></li>
                        <li><p>Page range of the article</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <title>Websites</title>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Author(s)</p></li>
                        <li><p>Title</p></li>
                        <li><p>Website name</p></li>
                        <li><p>Date published or updated</p></li>
                        <li><p>Date accessed</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </list>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>You might be asking us, <q>But why do I need all of this information?</q> No, citation guides are not out to get you! Each piece of a citation has a specific purpose. Here are some reasons behind the information you need. Hopefully this context will 1) help you understand what the citation is doing and why, and 2) help you use other people's sources more effectively!</p>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/citation-info-table"/>
            </sidebyside>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Tip</title>
                <p>Having trouble finding the right information in a source? Things like publishing location can sometimes be tricky to pinpoint. If you've looked all over the copyright page, title page, binding, and cover, just go to Google and search the publisher's name. You'll likely find the publisher's address, which should tell you what city the company is located in. Another trick is to look the book up on <url href="amazon.com">Amazon</url><mdash/>sometimes they'll have the right information in the <q>Product Details</q> section.</p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Finding Information in a Source</title>
            <p>Sometimes it can be hard to find the citation information you need in a source, especially when each is one is so different. While these are by no means a universal guide, the following images provide a general indication of where you can find citation info in different types of sources.</p>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Book with One Author</title>
        <introduction>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/Citations-BookOneAuthor"/>
            </sidebyside>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>APA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first initial.</red> <lightgreen>(Year).</lightgreen> <lightblue><i>Title of Work.</i></lightblue> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher.</lightpurple></p>
                <p><red>McCarthy, C.</red> <lightgreen>(2006).</lightgreen> <lightblue><i>The Road.</i></lightblue> <maroon>New York:</maroon> <lightpurple>Alfred A. Knopf.</lightpurple></p>
                <p>In-text: (McCarthy, 2006)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Chicago</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <lightblue><i>Title of Work.</i></lightblue> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>year.</lightgreen></p>
                <p><red>McCarthy, Cormac.</red> <lightblue><i>The Road.</i></lightblue> <maroon>New York:</maroon> <lightpurple>Alfred A. Knopf,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>2006.</lightgreen></p>
            </example>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Notes</title>
                <p>First appearance.<fn>Cormac McCarthy, <i>The Road</i> (New York: Alfred A. Knopf, 2006), 1<ndash/>2.</fn></p>
                <p>Consecutive appearances.<fn>Ibid., 34.</fn></p>
                <p>Non-consecutive appearances.<fn>McCarthy, <i>The Road,</i> 5.</fn></p>
                <p><em>For more information about how footnotes work, see Subsection 8.3.1.</em></p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>MLA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <lightblue><i>Title of Work.</i></lightblue> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>year.</lightgreen> <teal>Medium.</teal></p>
                <p><red>McCarthy, Cormac.</red> <lightblue><i>The Road.</i></lightblue> <maroon>New York:</maroon> <lightpurple>Alfred A. Knopf,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>2006.</lightgreen> <teal>Print.</teal></p>
                <p>In-text: (McCarthy 5)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Book with Multiple Authors</title>
        <introduction>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/Citations-BookMultipleAuthors"/>
            </sidebyside>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>APA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author 1 last name, first initial, <ampersand/> Author 2 last name, first initial</red> <lightgreen>(Year).</lightgreen> <lightblue><i>Title of Work.</i></lightblue> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher.</lightpurple></p>
                <p><red>Bowler, P. J., <ampersand/> Morus, I. R.</red> <lightgreen>(2005).</lightgreen> <lightblue>Making Modern Science: A Historical Survey.</lightblue> <maroon>Chicago:</maroon> <lightpurple>University of Chicago Press.</lightpurple></p>
                <p>In-text: (Bowler <ampersand/> Morus, 2005)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Chicago</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author 1 last name, first name, and Author 2 first name last name.</red> <lightblue><i>Title of Work.</i></lightblue> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon><lightpurple>Publisher,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>year.</lightgreen></p>
                <p><red>Bowler, Peter J., and Iwan Rhys Morus.</red> <lightblue><i>Making Modern Science: A Historical Survey.</i></lightblue> <maroon>Chicago:</maroon><lightpurple>University of Chicago Press,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>2005.</lightgreen></p>
            </example>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Notes</title>
                <p>First appearance.<fn>Peter J. Bowler and Iwan Rhys Morus, <i>Making Modern Science: A Historical Survey</i> (Chicago: University of Chicago Press), 20.</fn></p>
                <p>Consecutive appearances.<fn>Ibid., 47.</fn></p>
                <p>Non-consecutive appearances.<fn>Bowler and Morus, <i>Making Modern Science,</i> 5<ndash/>12.</fn></p>
                <p><em>For more information about how footnotes work, see Subsection 8.3.1.</em></p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>MLA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author 1 last name, first name, and Author 2 first name last name.</red> <lightblue><i>Title of Work.</i></lightblue> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>year.</lightgreen> <teal>Medium.</teal></p>
                <p><red>Bowler, Peter J., and Iwan Rhys Morus.</red> <lightblue><i>Making Modern Science: A Historical Survey.</i></lightblue> <maroon>Chicago:</maroon> <lightpurple>University of Chicago Press,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>2005.</lightgreen> <teal>Print.</teal></p>
                <p>In-text: (Bowler and Morus 12)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Edition Other than the First</title>
        <introduction>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/Citations-EditionOtherThanTheFirst"/>
            </sidebyside>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>APA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first initial.</red> <lightgreen>(Year).</lightgreen> <lightblue><i>Title of Work</i></lightblue> <lightpink>(edition number ed.).</lightpink> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher.</lightpurple></p>
                <p><red>Tannsjo, T.</red> <lightgreen>(2008).</lightgreen> <lightblue><i>Understanding Ethics: An Introduction to Moral Theory</i></lightblue> <lightpink>(2nd ed.).</lightpink> <maroon>Edinburgh:</maroon><lightpurple>University of Edinburgh Press.</lightpurple></p>
                <p>In-text: (Tannsjo, 2008)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Chicago</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <lightblue><i>Title of Work.</i></lightblue> <lightpink>Number edition Ed.</lightpink> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>year.</lightgreen></p>
                <p><red>Tannsjo, Torbjorn.</red> <lightblue><i>Understanding Ethics: an Introduction to Moral Theory.</i></lightblue> <lightpink>2nd Ed.</lightpink> <maroon>Edinburgh:</maroon> <lightpurple>University of Edinburgh Press,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>2008.</lightgreen></p>
            </example>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Notes</title>
                <p>First appearance.<fn>Torbjorn Tannsjo, <i>Understanding Ethics: an Introduction to Moral Theory,</i> 2nd ed. (Edinburgh: University of Edinburgh Press, 2008), 25.</fn></p>
                <p>Consecutive appearances.<fn>Ibid., 45.</fn></p>
                <p>Non-consecutive appearances.<fn>Tannsjo, <i>Understanding Ethics,</i> 27.</fn></p>
                <p><em>For more information about how footnotes work, see Subsection 8.3.1.</em></p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>MLA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <lightblue><i>Title of Work.</i></lightblue> <lightpink>Number edition Ed.</lightpink> <maroon>City of Publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>year.</lightgreen> <teal>Medium.</teal></p>
                <p><red>Tannsjo, Torbjorn.</red> <lightblue><i>Understanding Ethics: an Introduction to Moral Theory.</i></lightblue> <lightpink>2nd ed.</lightpink> <maroon>Edinburgh:</maroon> <lightpurple>University of Edinburgh Press,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>2008.</lightgreen> <teal>Print.</teal></p>
                <p>In-text: (Tannsjo 27)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Chapter in an Edited Book</title>
        <introduction>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/Citations-ChapterInEdited"/>
            </sidebyside>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>APA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first initial.</red> <lightgreen>(Year of publication).</lightgreen> <lightblue><q>Title of Chapter.</q></lightblue> In Editors' first initials last names (Eds.), <pink><i>Title of Anthology</i></pink> (pp. <blue>Page range</blue>). <maroon>City of publication, State:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher.</lightpurple></p>
                <p><red>Christoph, J. N.</red> <lightgreen>(2014).</lightgreen> <lightblue><q>Sponsoring Education for All: Revisiting the Sacred/Secular Divide in Twenty-First-Century Zanzibar.</q></lightblue> In J. Duffy, J. N. Christoph, E. Goldblatt, N. Graff, R. Nowacek, <ampersand/> B. Trabold (Eds.), <pink><i>Literacy, Economy, and Power: Writing and Research after Literacy in American Lives</i></pink> (pp. <blue>79<ndash/>96</blue>). <maroon>Carbondale, IL:</maroon> <lightpurple>Southern Illinois University Press.</lightpurple></p>
                <p>In-text: (Christoph, 2014)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Chicago</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <lightblue><q>Title of Chapter.</q></lightblue> In <pink><i>Title of Anthology,</i></pink> edited by Editors' first names last names, <blue>Page range.</blue> <maroon>City of publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>Year of publication.</lightgreen></p>
                <p><red>Christoph, Julie Nelson.</red> <lightblue><q>Sponsoring Education for All: Revisiting the Sacred/Secular Divide in Twenty-First-Century Zanzibar.</q></lightblue> In <pink><i>Literacy, Economy, and Power: Writing and Research after Literacy in American Lives,</i></pink> edited by John Duffy, Julie Nelson Christoph, Eli Goldblatt, Nelson Graff, Rebecca S. Nowacek, and Bryan Trabold, <blue>79<ndash/>96.</blue> <maroon>Carbondale:</maroon> <lightpurple>Southern Illinois University Press,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>2014.</lightgreen></p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>MLA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <lightblue><q>Title of Chapter.</q></lightblue> <pink><i>Title of Anthology.</i></pink> Eds. Editors' first names last names. <maroon>City of publication:</maroon> <lightpurple>Publisher,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>Year of publication.</lightgreen> <blue>Page range.</blue> <teal>Medium.</teal></p>
                <p><red>Christoph, Julie Nelson.</red> <lightblue><q>Sponsoring Education for All: Revisiting the Sacred/Secular Divide in Twenty-First-Century Zanzibar.</q></lightblue> <pink><i>Literacy, Economy, and Power: Writing and Research after Literacy in American Lives.</i></pink> Eds. John Duffy, Julie Nelson Christoph, Eli Goldblatt, Nelson Graff, Rebecca S. Nowacek, and Bryan Trabold. <maroon>Carbondale:</maroon> <lightpurple>Southern Illinois University Press,</lightpurple> <lightgreen>2014.</lightgreen> <blue>79<ndash/>96.</blue> <teal>Print.</teal></p>
                <p>In-text: (Christoph 79)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Book Review</title>
        <introduction>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/Citations-BookReview"/>
            </sidebyside>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>APA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first initial.</red> <lightgreen>(Year, Month of Publication).</lightgreen> [Review of the book <lightblue><i>Title of Reviewed Work</i>,</lightblue> by <gray>Author of Reviewed Work first name last name</gray>]. <pink><i>Name of Journal,</i></pink> <darkred>volume,</darkred> <blue>page range.</blue> <orange>Doi: xx.xxxxxx.</orange></p>
                <p><red>Paul, J. J.</red> <lightgreen>(2006, June).</lightgreen> [Review of the book <lightblue><i>Civilizing Natures: Race, Resources, and Modernity in Colonial South India</i>,</lightblue> by <gray>Kavita Philip</gray>]. <pink><i>Isis,</i></pink> <darkred>97,</darkred> <blue>370<ndash/>371.</blue> <orange>Doi: 10.1086/507384.</orange></p>
                <p>In-text: (Paul, 2006)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Chicago</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red>Review of <lightblue><i>Title of Reviewed Work,</i></lightblue> by <gray>Author of Reviewed Work First Last.</gray> <pink><i>Name of Journal</i></pink> <darkred>volume, no. issue</darkred> <lightgreen>(Year):</lightgreen> <blue>page range.</blue></p>
                <p><red>Paul, John J.</red>Review of <lightblue><i>Civilizing Natures: Race, Resources, and Modernity in Colonial South India,</i></lightblue> by <gray>Kavita Philip.</gray> <pink><i>Isis</i></pink> <darkred>97, no. 2</darkred> <lightgreen>(2006):</lightgreen> <blue>370<ndash/>371.</blue></p>
            </example>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Notes</title>
                <p>First appearance.<fn>John J. Paul, review of <i>Civilizing Natures: Race, Resources, and Modernity in Colonial South India,</i> by Kavita Philip, <i>Isis</i> 97, no. 2 (2006): 370<ndash/>371.</fn></p>
                <p>Consecutive appearances.<fn>Ibid., 371.</fn></p>
                <p>Non-consecutive appearances.<fn>Paul, review of <i>Civilizing Natures,</i> 370.</fn></p>
                <p><em>For more information about how footnotes work, see Subsection 8.3.1.</em></p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>MLA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Paul, John J.</red> <gray>Title of Review (if any).</gray> Rev. of <lightblue><i>Title of Reviewed Work,</i></lightblue> aut. <gray>Author of Reviewed Work.</gray> <pink><i>Name of Journal</i></pink> <darkred>volume.issue</darkred> <lightgreen>(Year):</lightgreen> <blue>page range.</blue> <teal>Medium.</teal></p>
                <p><red>Paul, John J.</red> Rev. of <lightblue><i>Civilizing Natures: Race, Resources, and Modernity in Colonial South India,</i></lightblue> aut. <gray>Kavita Philip.</gray> <pink><i>Isis</i></pink> <darkred>97.2</darkred> <lightgreen>(2006):</lightgreen> <blue>370<ndash/>371.</blue> <teal>Print.</teal></p>
                <p>In-text: (Paul 370)</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Print Article</title>
        <introduction>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/Citations-PrintArticle"/>
            </sidebyside>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>APA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first initial.</red> <lightgreen>(Year of publication).</lightgreen> <lightblue><q>Title of Article.</q></lightblue> <pink><i>Name of Journal</i></pink> <darkred>volume(issue),</darkred> <blue>page range.</blue></p>
                <p><red>Mann, S. A.</red> <lightgreen>(2011).</lightgreen> <lightblue>Pioneers of U.S. Ecofeminism and Environmental Justice.</lightblue> <pink><i>Feminist Formations</i></pink> <darkred>23(2),</darkred> <blue>1<ndash/>25.</blue></p>
                <p>In-text: (Mann, 2011)</p>
                <p>For an article found in an online journal, include the DOI<mdash/>or, if the article has no DOI, include the URL<mdash/>after the page range. Do not place a period at the end of the DOI or URL.</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Chicago</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <lightblue><q>Title of Article.</q></lightblue> <pink><i>Name of Journal</i></pink> <darkred>volume, no. issue</darkred> <lightgreen>(Year of publication):</lightgreen> <blue>page range.</blue></p>
                <p><red>Mann, Susan A.</red> <lightblue><q>Pioneers of U.S. Ecofeminism and Environmental Justice.</q></lightblue> <pink><i>Feminist Formations</i></pink> <darkred>23, no. 2</darkred> <lightgreen>(2011):</lightgreen> <blue>1<ndash/>25.</blue></p>
                <p>For an article found in an online journal, include the DOI<mdash/>or, if the article has no DOI, include the URL<mdash/>at the end of the citation. Place a period at the end of the DOI or URL.</p>
            </example>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Notes</title>
                <p>First appearance.<fn>Susan Mann. <q>Pioneers of U.S. Ecofeminism and Environmental Justice,</q> <i>Feminist Formations</i> 23, no. 2 (2011): 5.</fn></p>
                <p>Consecutive appearances.<fn>Ibid., 6.</fn></p>
                <p>Non-consecutive appearances.<fn>Mann, <q>Pioneers of U.S. Ecofeminism,</q> 10<ndash/>15.</fn></p>
                <p><em>For more information about how footnotes work, see Subsection 8.3.1.</em></p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>MLA</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <lightblue><q>Title of Article.</q></lightblue> <pink><i>Name of Journal</i></pink> <darkred>volume. issue</darkred> <lightgreen>(Year of publication):</lightgreen> <blue>page range.</blue> <teal>Medium.</teal></p>
                <p><red>Mann, Susan A.</red> <lightblue><q>Pioneers of U.S. Ecofeminism and Environmental Justice.</q></lightblue> <pink><i>Feminist Formations</i></pink> <darkred>23.2</darkred> <lightgreen>(2011):</lightgreen> <blue>1<ndash/>25.</blue> <teal>Print.</teal></p>
                <p>In-text: (Mann 10)</p>
                <p><em>For an article found in an online journal, indicate <q>Web</q> as the medium, and include the date of access after the medium. End the date of access with a period. If you find the article using a database, such as JSTOR or ProQuest, include the name of the database, italicized, between the page range and the medium and end place a period after the name.</em></p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Website</title>
        <introduction>
            <sidebyside>
                <image source="images/Citations-Website"/>
            </sidebyside>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>APA</title>
            <example>
                <p>APA does not provide a formal citation for citing websites.</p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Chicago</title>
            <example>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <darkgreen>Title of Website (leave unitalicized unless the title of the website is also the title of a book or periodical).</darkgreen> <gray>Sponsor.</gray> <lightgreen>Date of publication or date updated (if none, give date accessed).</lightgreen> <orange>URL.</orange></p>
                <p><red>Martin, Mark.</red> <darkgreen>Martin's Microbial Menagerie.</darkgreen> <gray>University of Puget Sound,</gray> <lightgreen>August 1, 2016.</lightgreen> <orange>http://webspace.pugetsound.edu/facultypages/momartin/index.htm</orange></p>
            </example>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Notes</title>
                <p>First appearance.<fn>Mark Martin, Martin's Microbial Menagerie, University of Puget Sound, August 1, 2016, <url href="http://webspace.pugetsound.edu/facultypages/momartin/index.htm"/>.</fn></p>
                <p>Consecutive appearances.<fn>Ibid.</fn></p>
                <p>Non-consecutive appearances.<fn>Martin, Martin's Microbial Menagerie.</fn></p>
                <p><em>If no known author is provided, begin the citation with the title of the website.</em></p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>MLA</title>
            <example>
                <title>Website with human author</title>
                <p><red>Author last name, first name.</red> <darkgreen><i>Title of Website.</i></darkgreen> <gray>Sponsor of site,</gray> <lightgreen>Date updated.</lightgreen> <teal>Medium.</teal> <navy>Date of access: day month year.</navy></p>
                <p><red>Martin, Mark.</red> <darkgreen><i>Martin's Microbial Menagerie.</i></darkgreen> <gray>University of Puget Sound,</gray> <lightgreen>n.d.</lightgreen> <teal>Web.</teal> <navy>1 Aug 2016.</navy></p>
                <p>In-Text: (Martin)</p>
            </example>
            <example>
                <title>Website with organization as author</title>
                <p><red>Organization.</red> <darkgreen><i>Title of Website.</i></darkgreen> <gray>Abbreviation of sponsor of site,</gray> <lightgreen>Date updated.</lightgreen> <teal>Medium.</teal> <navy>Date of access: day month year.</navy></p>
                <p><red>University of Puget Sound.</red> <darkgreen><i>University of Puget Sound.</i></darkgreen> <gray>UPS,</gray> <lightgreen>2016.</lightgreen> <teal>Web.</teal> <navy>29 July 2016.</navy></p>
                <p><ul>
                    <li>For a website with no known author, begin the citation with the title of the website.</li>
                    <li>For a website with no known title, use a description such as <q>Main page</q> instead of a title.</li>
                </ul></p>
                <p>In-Text: (University of Puget Sound)</p>
            </example>
